‘Cousin Kate’ and ‘What Were They Like?’ both use powerful imagery to show the suffering that
loss brings. In ‘Cousin Kate’, Rossetti uses animalistic imagery, such as , to convey the depths of
the abandoned speaker’s despair. The dehumanising description of the speaker as emphasises how
isolated from human society she feels. Similarly, in ‘What Were they Like?’, the graphic phrase
creates a vividly emotive image of how humanity had been lost during the war — people were reduced
to ‘things’. This has a powerful effect on the reader, who may struggle to comprehend such brutality.
Rossetti suggests that the speaker resents Kate for taking her place at the lord’s side. Her
repetition of is tinged with bitter sarcasm, and emphasises her frustration at having lost her own
‘purity’. The frustrated tone of ‘Cousin Kate’ contrasts with the poignancy of ‘What Were They Like?’,
which juxtaposes images of rural life, like , with harrowing descriptions of destruction. This gives the
poem a solemn tone and emphasises the profound sense of loss. This sensation is deepened by phrases
of uncertainty like , which reveal that the losses were so great, their true extent may never be known.
